---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import ReportPreview from "../components/ReportPreview.astro";
import WorkflowSteps from "../components/WorkflowSteps.astro";

const description = "AntennaBench is a local-first macOS app for repeatable WSPR antenna comparisons, with guided experiments and evidence-first reports.";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="AntennaBench — Better antenna comparisons, evidence included"
  socialTitle="Better antenna comparisons, evidence included"
  description={description}
  canonicalPath="/"
>
  <section class="hero section-pad">
    <div class="shell hero-grid">
      <div class="hero-copy">
        <p class="status-pill"><span></span> Early preview · run from source</p>
        <h1>Better antenna comparisons. <em>Evidence included.</em></h1>
        <p class="hero-lede">
          Propagation changes. Receivers come and go. Switches happen late.
          AntennaBench turns a WSPR comparison into a guided, repeatable experiment—and
          keeps the limits visible beside the result.
        </p>
        <div class="button-row">
          <a class="button button-primary" href="/sample-report/summary/">Read the Summary</a>
          <a class="button button-secondary" href="/how-it-works/">See how it works</a>
        </div>
        <ul class="trust-list" aria-label="Product boundaries">
          <li>Local-first</li>
          <li>No account required</li>
          <li>Your bundle stays authoritative</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="hero-visual" aria-label="Stylized antenna comparison evidence">
        <div class="signal-orbit orbit-one"></div>
        <div class="signal-orbit orbit-two"></div>
        <div class="signal-orbit orbit-three"></div>
        <div class="antenna-glyph">
          <span class="antenna-dot"></span>
          <span class="antenna-stem"></span>
          <span class="antenna-base"></span>
        </div>
        <div class="evidence-card evidence-card-a">
          <span>Experiment record</span>
          <strong>Plan ≠ action</strong>
          <small>observations stay attributed</small>
        </div>
        <div class="evidence-card evidence-card-b">
          <span>Report boundary</span>
          <strong>Result + limits</strong>
          <small>no invented winner</small>
        </div>
        <p class="visual-caption">Illustrative interface motif; see the real generated report below.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="tension-band" aria-labelledby="problem-title">
    <div class="shell tension-grid">
      <p class="eyebrow">The problem</p>
      <div>
        <h2 id="problem-title">A stronger signal is only useful when you know what produced it.</h2>
        <p>
          A quick A/B test can confuse propagation, timing, receiver coverage, and missing
          data with antenna performance. AntennaBench records the plan, what the operator
          actually did, and what each source observed as different facts.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section-pad workflow-section" aria-labelledby="workflow-title">
    <div class="shell">
      <div class="section-heading">
        <p class="eyebrow">A guided experiment</p>
        <h2 id="workflow-title">From a clear question to a report you can audit</h2>
        <p>
          The first supported workflow uses WSPR’s fixed two-minute cadence to alternate
          antennas while changing conditions are distributed across the run.
        </p>
      </div>
      <WorkflowSteps />
      <div class="centered-link">
        <a class="text-link" href="/how-it-works/">Walk through the complete workflow <span aria-hidden="true">→</span></a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="availability-section" aria-labelledby="network-choice-title">
    <div class="shell availability-grid">
      <div>
        <p class="eyebrow">Why WSPR?</p>
        <h2 id="network-choice-title">The default is about experiment design, not mode loyalty.</h2>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p>
          In the measured 40, 20, and 15 meter snapshot, WSPR exposed more reporting paths
          and a broader occupied-grid footprint, while its fixed cadence made repeated A/B
          cycles easier to control. RBN remains the better answer when the question is how
          your actual CW or RTTY signal is being copied.
        </p>
        <a class="button button-light" href="/why-wspr/">See WSPR and RBN side by side <span aria-hidden="true">→</span></a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section-pad report-section" aria-labelledby="report-title">
    <div class="shell report-grid">
      <div class="report-copy">
        <p class="eyebrow">A real generated report</p>
        <h2 id="report-title">Start with the answer. Keep the evidence close.</h2>
        <p>
          Summary is the ordinary reading and sharing path. It leads with what the run
          showed, keeps each evidence population separate, and puts support counts and the
          principal limitation beside the result.
        </p>
        <ul class="check-list">
          <li>Paired shared-path signal with explicit support</li>
          <li>Common-opportunity detection kept separate from observed reach</li>
          <li>Uncontrolled paths described without turning missing spots into zeroes</li>
          <li>Full evidence available for the complete human-readable audit</li>
        </ul>
        <div class="button-row report-actions">
          <a class="button button-dark" href="/sample-report/summary/">Read the Summary</a>
          <a class="button button-secondary" href="/sample-report/">Open Full evidence</a>
        </div>
        <p class="fine-print">
          Both documents are generated from one real, sanitized station session. They are
          derived views; the lossless session bundle remains the durable record. This site
          does not accept uploads or host operator reports. You can also
          <a href="/sample-report/inconclusive/">see an inconclusive example</a> with no
          shared paths.
        </p>
      </div>
      <ReportPreview />
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section-pad principles-section" aria-labelledby="principles-title">
    <div class="shell">
      <div class="section-heading compact-heading">
        <p class="eyebrow">Designed around the evidence</p>
        <h2 id="principles-title">Useful without becoming a black box</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="principle-grid">
        <article>
          <span aria-hidden="true">01</span>
          <h3>Local-first by default</h3>
          <p>Plan, run, recover, review, and export without an account or hosted service.</p>
        </article>
        <article>
          <span aria-hidden="true">02</span>
          <h3>The bundle is the record</h3>
          <p>Reports are derived views. The portable session bundle keeps the durable evidence.</p>
        </article>
        <article>
          <span aria-hidden="true">03</span>
          <h3>Uncertainty stays visible</h3>
          <p>Gaps, corrections, source boundaries, and insufficient evidence remain part of the result.</p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="availability-section" aria-labelledby="availability-title">
    <div class="shell availability-grid">
      <div>
        <p class="eyebrow">Current availability</p>
        <h2 id="availability-title">An early preview for contributors and evaluators</h2>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p>
          AntennaBench currently runs from source on macOS 15 or later. The local workflow
          can conduct manual WSPR comparisons and export reports and verified bundles.
          There is not yet a signed end-user download, hosted report publishing, account,
          or automatic antenna conclusion.
        </p>
        <a class="button button-light" href="https://github.com/rwjblue/antennabench">View the project on GitHub <span aria-hidden="true">↗</span></a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
